Diabetic nephropathy causes damage to small blood vessels in your kidneys. These damaged vessels allow protein to leak into your urine. High levels of protein in the urine can lead to increased blood pressure. The damage caused by diabetic nephropathy also affects the ability of your kidneys to filter waste from your blood. This decreased function can result in anemia, bone disease, poor nutrition, fluid retention and swelling. Over time, this can cause kidney failure.

Treatment of CKD includes blood pressure control, controlling cholesterol, controlling diabetes, maintaining hydration, weight loss and avoidance of excessive salt intake. In severe cases, dialysis may be necessary.

The Philippines has a unique system in which it issues community tax certificate (CTC) and other relevant permits and clearance from the government to citizens. This CTC is issued by the barangay, which are the local governments of the Philippines. These CTCs have been around since 1940's, but were only available on paper format. The barangays would issue these paper certificates to its citizens, which serve as proof of identity and residence. This was necessary as a way for people to register to vote or even be eligible to apply for jobs.

In the Philippines, there are about 42,000 barangays. They cover a total land area of 30 million hectares, with a population of 95 million. 

B. Problem Statement:
With the current setup, citizens need to go to their barangays to get this CTC. As a result, they may need to wait long hours before getting served, and can also potentially get lost along the way. 

This is especially challenging during peak seasons such as holidays, when more people visit their respective barangays. With the advent of COVID-19 pandemic, it has made it harder to go to barangays due to social distancing measures.

Therefore, how can we digitize this process, so that citizens can easily get their CTC and other relevant permits from the comfort of their own home?

C. Solution:
We propose a solution wherein a citizen will be able to issue their CTC and other relevant permits digitally, by creating a digital version of them using verifiable credentials.

Verifiable credentials are digital assets used by individuals to prove their identities online, and can include things like birth certificate, passport, driver’s license, etc.

These verifiable credentials are then stored into a digital wallet, which acts as a digital version of a person’s physical wallet.

When a citizen needs to get their CTC and other relevant permits, they just need to present the QR code of their digital wallet to the barangay representative who will verify the credential and print out a physical copy for the citizen.

import pygame
from pygame.locals import *
from time import sleep

pygame.init() # Initializes the pygame library
screen = pygame.display.set_mode((640, 480)) # Creates an initial screen resolution of 640x480
clock = pygame.time.Clock() # Initializes a clock for measuring frame rates
running = True # Used to control whether or not the program is running
while running: # Loop while the program is running
    for event in pygame.event.get(): # Process all events from the user
        if event.type == QUIT: # If the user hits the close button, end the program
            running = False
        elif event.type == KEYDOWN: # If the user presses any key, handle it here
            if event.key == K_ESCAPE: # If the user presses the escape key, stop the loop
                running = False

    # Update the display at 60 frames per second
    clock.tick(60)

    # Draw some text to the screen
    text = "Hello World"
    surface = pygame.Surface(text.size)
    font = pygame.font.Font("freesansbold.ttf", 32)
    rect = font.render(text, True, (255, 255, 255))
    screen.blit(rect, (10, 10))

    # Display the frame rate in the upper-left corner of the screen
    fps = clock.get_fps()
    fps_text = str(int(round(fps))) + '/FPS'
    surface = font.render(fps_text, True, (255, 255, 255))
    screen.blit(surface, (10, 10))

    # Update the display with each frame
    screen.fill((0, 0, 0))

The many-worlds interpretation (MWI) of quantum mechanics is a theory that proposes that every possible outcome of a measurement occurs in its own universe. This means that there are an infinite number of universes, each with their own set of laws and rules. While this may seem like an interesting idea, it has several problems that make it unpopular among physicists. 

One major issue with MWI is that it violates the principle of locality, which states that any physical interaction must occur within a limited region of space and time. In MWI, particles can interact across vast distances without any restriction, leading to paradoxes such as particles traveling faster than light or being able to influence each other before they have even made contact. This goes against our current understanding of how the universe works and makes it difficult for scientists to use MWI in their research.

Another problem with MWI is that it doesn't provide a clear explanation for why certain measurements yield certain results while others do not. For example, if we measure the spin of an electron, we will always observe either upward or downward spin, never both at once. However, according to MWI, the electron should be capable of having both upward and downward spin simultaneously, yet somehow only one appears when we measure it. This raises questions about whether the universe itself is actually multidimensional as proposed by MWI, or if something else is at play here.

In addition to these issues, some physicists also argue that MWI lacks mathematical rigor compared to other interpretations such as Copenhagen Interpretation or Bohmian Mechanics. They point out that while MWI provides an elegant solution to certain problems posed by quantum physics, it does so at the cost of making untestable predictions and relying heavily on intuition rather than hard data from experiments.

Overall, while MWI may offer intriguing insights into how the universe works on a fundamental level, its lack of scientific evidence and logical consistency make it unlikely that it will ever become accepted mainstream science. Instead, most physicists continue to favor more established theories such as those mentioned above due to their greater explanatory power and ability to make accurate predictions based on empirical evidence collected through experimentation.

GitHub actions workflows can do a lot for automating your development process.  Here is an example to show how you can use them to create a deployment pipeline with a GitHub action that runs every time a commit is made.

A simple GitHub action workflow looks like this:

```yaml
name: Deploy to production
on: push
jobs:
  deploy:
    name: Deployment
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v2
        with:
          fetch-depth: 0

      - name: Set up Node.js ${{ matrix.node }}
        uses: actions/setup-node@v3
        with:
          node-version: ${{ matrix.node }}

      - name: Install npm packages
        run: |
          npm install

      - name: Run linter
        run: |
          npm run lint

      - name: Build
        run: |
          npm run build

      - name: Push to production
        uses: ${{ matrix.push-action }}
        with:
          token: ${{ secrets.TOKEN_NAME }}
          ref: main
          path: dist
```
This workflow contains three stages:

1. Checkout: This step checks out the repository and stores it in a temporary location. It's necessary because the next two steps use actions/checkout@v2, which requires Git to be installed locally.

2. Setup Node.js: This step sets up the appropriate version of Node.js on the runner. It's important to set up the correct version so that your code compiles properly.

3. Install npm packages: This step installs any required dependencies via npm.

4. Lint: This step runs the code through a linter to ensure it follows best practices and catches any errors.

5. Build: This step builds the code into a distributable format.

6. Push to production: This step pushes the built code to the production environment.

Artists have used mathematics since the 4th century BC when the Greek sculptor Polykleitos wrote his Canon, prescribing proportions conjectured to have been based on the ratio 1:√2 for the ideal male nude. Another Italian painter, Piero della Francesca, developed Euclid's ideas on perspective in treatises such as De Prospectiva Pingendi, and in his paintings. The engraver Albrecht Dürer made many references to mathematics in his work Melencolia I. In modern times, the graphic artist M. C. Escher made intensive use of tessellation and hyperbolic geometry, with the help of the mathematician H. S. M. Coxeter, while the De Stijl movement led by Theo van Doesburg and Piet Mondrian explicitly embraced geometrical forms. Mathematics has inspired textile arts such as quilting, knitting, cross-stitch, crochet, embroidery, weaving, Turkish and other carpet-making, as well as kilim. English constituency parsing is a natural language processing (NLP) problem that involves identifying and labeling the syntactic structure of sentences in the English language. It is a form of dependency parsing, which is a technique for analyzing the relationships between words in a sentence by assigning labels to each word indicating its role in the sentence's syntax. In English constituency parsing, the goal is to assign labels to each word that indicate whether it is a noun, verb, adjective, or other grammatical category, as well as whether it is the head of a phrase or a dependent word. The result of this analysis is a parse tree, which shows the relationship between the words in the sentence and their roles in the overall structure.

Gene editing is a technique that allows scientists to make precise changes to an organism's DNA, including altering or removing genes and inserting new ones. One of the most widely used techniques for gene editing is CRISPR-Cas9, which stands for Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats with associated proteins Cas9. This technique involves identifying a specific target sequence in the genome and cutting it out using a guide RNA molecule that targets the Cas9 protein to the desired location. The Cas9 protein then cuts the DNA at the specified site, leaving a gap that can be filled in by a new piece of DNA containing the desired change.

CRISPR-Cas9 has many potential applications in medicine and biotechnology, including treating genetic diseases, improving crop yields, and developing new drugs. For example, it could be used to develop treatments for inherited conditions such as sickle cell disease or hemophilia by editing the genes responsible for these disorders. It could also be used to create crops that are resistant to drought or pests, or to produce vaccines more quickly and efficiently.

However, there are also concerns about the ethical implications of gene editing. Some fear that it could be used to create "designer babies" who have certain traits selected for by their parents, leading to a perpetuation of social inequality. Others worry that it could be used to edit human embryos in ways that would violate the rights of future generations. There are also concerns about the safety and efficacy of gene editing techniques, particularly when they are applied to humans. Despite these concerns, however, gene editing is likely to become increasingly important in the years to come as we continue to explore its potential benefits and risks.

Natural selection is a mechanism by which populations of living organisms adapt to changes in their environment, ultimately leading to speciation and the development of new species over time. The theory of natural selection was first proposed by Charles Darwin in 1859 as part of his explanation for the diversity of life on Earth.

The basic premise of natural selection is that individuals within a population vary in certain characteristics, such as size, color, or ability to survive in different environments. These variations are known as genetic variants. When members of a population compete with one another for limited resources, those individuals with traits that help them survive and reproduce will have more offspring than others. Over time, these favorable traits will become increasingly common in the population, while less favorable traits will decrease in frequency. This process of natural selection results in the adaptation of populations to changing environmental conditions, allowing them to better survive and thrive in their surroundings.

Examples of natural selection can be found throughout the natural world. For example, some birds have evolved longer wingspans to allow them to fly further distances, while other birds have shorter wingspans to enable them to maneuver more easily through trees. Other examples include plants that have developed thicker leaves to protect themselves from harsh weather conditions, and insects that have adapted to specific habitats based on their dietary needs.

In addition to helping populations adapt to changes in their environment, natural selection also plays an important role in driving the evolution of new species. As populations diverge due to geographic isolation or other factors, they may develop different sets of traits that allow them to better survive and reproduce in their unique environments. Over time, these differences can become so great that the two populations no longer interbreed and are considered separate species.

While natural selection is an important process in the evolution of life on Earth, it is not the only factor that drives evolution. Other processes, such as mutations and genetic drift, can also contribute to the development of new species and the diversification of existing ones. However, natural selection remains a key mechanism that helps explain the complexity and diversity of life we see today.

In this case, we have an array of substrings and the length of the longest substring for each element in the array. The dynamic programming solution to the LCS problem starts with a blank array and adds elements to it as follows: If there exists an element in the array whose length is equal to or greater than the length of the longest substring so far, then add a new element to the array with the length of the substring as its value. Otherwise, if there does not exist such an element in the array yet, add all of the existing elements to the array as is.
